The satire contains in'itsell its own best commentary. lt is a bit ol humorous and not unsriendly irony, directed primarily against some person whose name is ostentatiously withheld and, more broadly‚ against the science and art ol gastronomy. So far as there is any per- sonality in it, it is of a kind which would be especially understood and appreciated by Horace's intimate friends, and the satire belongs, in this respect, to the same class as Sat. 1, 9 and Sat. 2, 8.
